-- The constructor / anonymous-tuple component coercion limitation, pinned
-- (see Test/coercion_matrix_test.math, Stage 2 audit). A plain function
-- argument with a CONCRETE domain coerces an off-by-congruence proof
-- (`consume(h)` with `consume : (successor a = successor b) → _` and
-- `h : a = b`). But when the component's type is an INFERRED inductive
-- PARAMETER — here `And.introduction`'s first argument, whose type is the
-- parameter `A` solved from the expected `And(...)` — the coercion at the
-- argument site runs against an as-yet-unsolved metavariable and is a
-- no-op, so the bare `h` is rejected. This is an inference-ordering
-- limitation (the expected result type isn't unified into the
-- constructor's parameters before its components are elaborated), NOT a
-- missing coercion call. If a future bidirectional-elaboration change
-- solves the parameters first, this case starts verifying clean and the
-- corpus flags it — the cue to delete it and add the positive matrix cell.

module corpus.tuple_component_inferred_param_no_coerce

import axioms
import Logic.basics
import Equality.basics
import Natural.basics
import Natural.peano

theorem tuple_component_gap (a b : Natural) (h : a = b)
        : And(successor(a) = successor(b), True) :=
  ⟨h, True.trivial⟩
